        <h2>Your First BJJ Competition: A Guide for Restigouche Dojo Athletes</h2>
    </div>
    
    <!--CONTENT-->
    <div class="content-area">
        <div class="wrapper-body">
            <section class="hero">
                <div class="container">
                    <h2 id="title">Welcome, Restigouche Dojo Warriors!</h2>
                    <p id="program-description">
                        Congratulations on taking the step to compete in your first Brazilian Jiu-Jitsu (BJJ) tournament. Competing is a fantastic way to test your skills, gain experience, and grow as a martial artist. This guide will help you prepare both physically and mentally for the challenge ahead.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </section>
            <section class="features">
                <div class="container">
                    <h2 id="why-restigouche-dojo">Preparing for Your First BJJ Competition</h2>
                    <div class="feature-item">
                        <h3 id="reason-one">1. Set Clear Goals</h3>
                        <p id="reason-one-text">
                            Understand why you’re competing. Is it to test your skills, gain experience, or simply push your boundaries? Having a clear purpose will help you stay focused and motivated.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="feature-item">
                        <h3 id="reason-two">2. Develop a Game Plan</h3>
                        <p id="reason-two-text">
                            A game plan is essential for success. This isn’t just a vague idea but a detailed strategy for every possible scenario:
                            <ul>
                                <li><strong>Starting Position:</strong> Decide whether you’ll aim for a takedown or pull guard.</li>
                                <li><strong>Top Positions:</strong> Know your go-to moves for passing guard and maintaining control.</li>
                                <li><strong>Bottom Positions:</strong> Have specific sweeps and escapes drilled into muscle memory.</li>
                                <li><strong>Submissions:</strong> Focus on a few high-percentage submissions that you can execute well.</li>
                                <li><strong>Defense:</strong> Be prepared to defend against common attacks and recover from bad positions.</li>
                            </ul>
                        </p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="feature-item">
                        <h3 id="reason-three">3. Train Smart</h3>
                        <p id="reason-three-text">
                            Consistency is key. Regular training sessions will improve your techniques, stamina, and overall fitness:
                            <ul>
                                <li><strong>Spar with Different Partners:</strong> This will expose you to various styles and body types.</li>
                                <li><strong>Drill, Drill, Drill:</strong> Repetition builds proficiency. Focus on the techniques in your game plan.</li>
                                <li><strong>Conditioning:</strong> Incorporate cardio, strength training, and flexibility exercises. Jump rope, running, and bodyweight exercises are excellent choices.</li>
                            </ul>
                        </p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="feature-item">
                        <h3 id="reason-four">4. Mental Preparation</h3>
                        <p id="reason-four-text">
                            Your mindset is just as important as your physical preparation:
                            <ul>
                                <li><strong>Relax and Breathe:</strong> Learn to control your breathing. Practice deep diaphragm breathing: inhale through your nose for four seconds, fill your lungs, and exhale through your mouth for eight seconds.</li>
                                <li><strong>Visualization:</strong> Picture your matches in your mind. See yourself executing your game plan, staying calm, and handling any challenges. Always visualize positive outcomes.</li>
                                <li><strong>Stay Positive:</strong> Replace negative thoughts with positive affirmations. Believe in your training and your ability to perform well.</li>
                            </ul>
                        </p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="feature-item">
                        <h3 id="reason-five">5. Understand the Rules</h3>
                        <p id="reason-five-text">
                            Familiarize yourself with the tournament’s rules and point system:
                            <ul>
                                <li><strong>Takedown or Throw:</strong> 2 points</li>
                                <li><strong>Sweep:</strong> 2 points</li>
                                <li><strong>Knee on Belly:</strong> 2 points</li>
                                <li><strong>Passing the Guard:</strong> 3 points</li>
                                <li><strong>Mount Position:</strong> 4 points</li>
                            </ul>
                            Understanding the rules will boost your confidence and help you strategize effectively.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="feature-item">
                        <h3 id="reason-six">6. Gear Up</h3>
                        <p id="reason-six-text">
                            Ensure you have the correct gear:
                            <ul>
                                <li><strong>Gi:</strong> Make sure your gi is IBJJF-legal or meets the specific tournament’s requirements. It should be clean and in good condition.</li>
                                <li><strong>Belt:</strong> Wear a belt that corresponds to your rank.</li>
                                <li><strong>Mouthguard:</strong> Protect your teeth.</li>
                                <li><strong>Extras:</strong> Bring a spare gi, water, snacks, and any other personal items you may need.</li>
                            </ul>
                        </p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="feature-item">
                        <h3 id="reason-seven">7. Warm-Up Properly</h3>
                        <p id="reason-seven-text">
                            A good warm-up helps calm your mind and prepare your body:
                            <ul>
                                <li><strong>Routine:</strong> Perform a familiar warm-up routine that you do before training sessions.</li>
                                <li><strong>Focus:</strong> Concentrate on your movements and breathing, not the upcoming matches.</li>
                            </ul>
                        </p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="feature-item">
                        <h3 id="reason-eight">8. Nutrition and Hydration</h3>
                        <p id="reason-eight-text">
                            Your performance depends on how well you fuel your body:
                            <ul>
                                <li><strong>Hydrate:</strong> Drink plenty of water leading up to the competition.</li>
                                <li><strong>Eat Smart:</strong> Consume a balanced diet rich in proteins, carbohydrates, and healthy fats. On the day of the competition, eat light, easily digestible foods.</li>
                            </ul>
                        </p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="feature-item">
                        <h3 id="reason-nine">9. On Competition Day</h3>
                        <p id="reason-nine-text">
                            - <strong>Arrive Early:</strong> Give yourself plenty of time to check in, warm up, and get mentally prepared.<br>
                            - <strong>Stay Calm:</strong> Use your breathing techniques and visualization to stay relaxed.<br>
                            - <strong>Trust Your Training:</strong> Believe in your preparation and follow your game plan.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="feature-item">
                        <h3 id="reason-ten">10. Post-Competition Reflection</h3>
                        <p id="reason-ten-text">
                            No matter the outcome, every competition is a learning experience:
                            <ul>
                                <li><strong>Feedback:</strong> Seek feedback from your coach and teammates. Identify areas for improvement.</li>
                                <li><strong>Reflect:</strong> Think about what went well and what didn’t. Use this to guide your future training.</li>
                            </ul>
                        </p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </section>
